Moralical dilemmas for Fannie and Freddie  (Note: The word "Moralische" is an adjective derived from the noun "Moral," so it translates to "moral" in English. "Dilemmata" is the plural form of "Dilemma," which is also used in English. "Fannie and Freddie" refers to Fannie Mae and Freddie Mac, the housing finance agencies, and this name remains unchanged in translation.)
NEW HAVEN: The takeover of the mortgage giants Fannie Mae and Freddie Mac by the U.S. government represents a massive bailout of the creditors of these institutions, whose losses have continued to balloon in light of falling housing prices.
Now that the government is fully guaranteeing Fannies and Freddies' debts, American taxpayers will have to pay for everything that is not covered by the inadequate financial resources of their creditors.
Why such a rescue operation in the openly capitalist country of the world?
Does not the time-honored principle of capitalism require those who believed in the housing bubble and invested their money in Fannie Mae and Freddie Mac now to accept their losses?
Is it fair that innocent taxpayers have to suffer from their mistakes?
The answers to these questions would be obvious if the moral problems of the current financial crisis were clearly defined.
But they are not.
The main point is unclear whether the bailout will actually cost US taxpayers anything in the end. Perhaps it prevents further systemic effects that could bring the financial sector, and thereby the world economy, to its knees.
Just because systemic effects are difficult to quantify does not mean they do not exist.
Moreover, the securities issued by Fannie and Freddie were widely regarded as being backed by an implicit guarantee of the US government.
Although there was no official guarantee, the absence of a rescue action by the U.S. government could undermine confidence in government securities and, because they are associated with these, also in other financial titles.
The problems extend well beyond the US economy.
The world economy has been driven in recent years by notable speculative booms and busts in asset values, which bring questions of trust as well as fairness into the equation.
Similarly, similar housing sector booms are coming to an end in many other countries as well, and they may be facing the same trials – and the same moral dilemmas – that the U.S. economy is currently experiencing.
And the problem is not just the housing markets.
The stock markets are no exception.
The Chinese Shanghai Composite Index rose by a factor of five between 2005 and 2007 and then lost two-thirds of its real value.
The Sensex in India rose realistically by a factor of 5 between 2003 and 2007 and has since then lost a third of its value.
Similar stock market highs and lows have occurred in many other countries as well.
As long as they continued, the boom phases preceding these crashes led to overheating of these economies.
Now that they have reversed, a loss of trust could grip the world economy and plunge it into recession.
To prevent this, some selected bailouts might be necessary – not to support the market, but to address injustices.
There is no precise science of trust, no way to predict how people will react when, in the face of collapsing markets, help is not forthcoming.
The reactions of people to these events depend on their feelings and their sense of justice.
The described boom-and-bust cycles have caused a significant redistribution of wealth.
Those who invested on the stock market or in real estate did well or poorly depending on the timing.
People will judge the fairness of these results based on what they were told and what implicit promises they inferred from it.
What was told to the people in all these countries about the markets into which they invested their money?
Did everything really correspond to the truth?
Unfortunately, there is no way to find out.
The policy can only respond generally and cannot address all cases individually.
We know that the economic growth of recent times was spectacular in many countries.
But were the capital investments sold too expensively in their markets?
Have cynical salesmen here and elsewhere led people to believe that boom times would bring prosperity for all?
It is certain that, despite there having been a lot of "cheap talk" – general advice with reservations – most of the losers in this game are not scraping the bottom of the barrel.
However, we cannot draw carefree conclusions that all their losses should be tolerated without limitation.
The nagging problem is one of "faith and loyalty".
Volkswirtschafts systems flourish only when "honesty and trust" reign.
The current situation, in which speculative boom rides have driven the world economy forward – and are now, after their collapse, pushing it into recession – suggests that people who have promoted certain capital investments have acted in bad faith.
The sentence translates to: "Take the investors who have signed bonds from Fannie and Freddie."
Although the US government never officially promised to come to their aid in times of need, it established a special agency, the Office of Federal Housing Enterprise Oversight, whose task was to assess their strength in an annual report.
But this agency never admitted that there was a housing bubble.
The top officials of the government never issued a warning.
Can we really claim that investors must bear all the consequences of their losses?
How could this be fair?
The world is discovering the power of capitalism and its role in transforming economies.
But capitalism relies on honesty and trust.
An unfairly perceived treatment can be fatal for economic growth, as it means that people lose trust in companies and are therefore less willing to provide them with their valuable capital and labor.
Would such a result be morally preferable to a bailout?
